    {
      "content": "Blob Storage",
      "pos": [
        7472,
        7484
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For users with large amounts of unstructured data to store in the cloud, Blob storage offers a cost-effective and scalable solution.",
      "pos": [
        7486,
        7618
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use Blob storage to store content such as:",
      "pos": [
        7619,
        7669
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Documents",
      "pos": [
        7673,
        7682
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Social data such as photos, videos, music, and blogs",
      "pos": [
        7686,
        7738
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Backups of files, computers, databases, and devices",
      "pos": [
        7741,
        7792
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Images and text for web applications",
      "pos": [
        7795,
        7831
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Configuration data for cloud applications",
      "pos": [
        7834,
        7875
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Big data, such as logs and other large datasets",
      "pos": [
        7878,
        7925
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Every blob is organized into a container.",
      "pos": [
        7927,
        7968
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Containers also provide a useful way to assign security policies to groups of objects.",
      "pos": [
        7969,
        8055
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A storage account can contain any number of containers, and a container can contain any number of blobs, up to the 500 TB capacity limit of the storage account.",
      "pos": [
        8056,
        8216
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Blob storage offers three types of blobs, block blobs, append blobs, and page blobs (disks).",
      "pos": [
        8220,
        8312
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Block blobs are optimized for streaming and storing cloud objects, and are a good choice for storing documents, media files, backups etc. Append blobs are similar to block blobs, but are optimized for append operations.",
      "pos": [
        8313,
        8532
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An append blob can be updated only by adding a new block to the end.",
      "pos": [
        8533,
        8601
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Append blobs are a good choice for scenarios such as logging, where new data needs to be written only to the end of the blob.",
      "pos": [
        8602,
        8727
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Page blobs are optimized for representing IaaS disks and supporting random writes, and may be up to 1 TB in size.",
      "pos": [
        8729,
        8842
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An Azure virtual machine network attached IaaS disk is a VHD stored as a page blob.",
      "pos": [
        8843,
        8926
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For very large datasets where network constraints make uploading or downloading data to Blob storage over the wire unrealistic, you can ship a hard drive to Microsoft to import or export data directly from the data center using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Import/Export Service<ept id=\"p1\">](storage-import-export-service.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8928,
        9224
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also copy blob data within your storage account or across storage accounts.",
      "pos": [
        9225,
        9308
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Table Storage",
      "pos": [
        9314,
        9327
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Modern applications often demand data stores with greater scalability and flexibility than previous generations of software required.",
      "pos": [
        9329,
        9462
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Table storage offers highly available, massively scalable storage, so that your application can automatically scale to meet user demand.",
      "pos": [
        9463,
        9599
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Table storage is Microsoft’s NoSQL key/attribute store – it has a schemaless design, making it different from traditional relational databases.",
      "pos": [
        9600,
        9743
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "With a schemaless data store, it's easy to adapt your data as the needs of your application evolve.",
      "pos": [
        9744,
        9843
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Table storage is easy to use, so developers can create applications quickly.",
      "pos": [
        9844,
        9920
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Access to data is fast and cost-effective for all kinds of applications.",
      "pos": [
        9921,
        9993
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Table storage is typically significantly lower in cost than traditional SQL for similar volumes of data.",
      "pos": [
        9995,
        10099
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Table storage is a key-attribute store, meaning that every value in a table is stored with a typed property name.",
      "pos": [
        10101,
        10214
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The property name can be used for filtering and specifying selection criteria.",
      "pos": [
        10215,
        10293
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A collection of properties and their values comprise an entity.",
      "pos": [
        10294,
        10357
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since Table storage is schemaless, two entities in the same table can contain different collections of properties, and those properties can be of different types.",
      "pos": [
        10358,
        10520
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use Table storage to store flexible datasets, such as user data for web applications, address books, device information, and any other type of metadata that your service requires.",
      "pos": [
        10523,
        10710
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can store any number of entities in a table, and a storage account may contain any number of tables, up to the capacity limit of the storage account.",
      "pos": [
        10712,
        10865
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Like Blobs and Queues, developers can manage and access Table Storage using standard REST protocols, however Table Storage also supports a subset of the OData protocol, simplifying advanced querying capabilities and enabling both JSON and AtomPub (XML based) formats.",
      "pos": [
        10867,
        11134
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For today's Internet-based applications, NoSQL databases like Table storage offer a popular alternative to traditional relational databases.",
      "pos": [
        11136,
        11276
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Queue Storage",
      "pos": [
        11282,
        11295
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In designing applications for scale, application components are often decoupled, so that they can scale independently.",
      "pos": [
        11297,
        11415
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Queue storage provides a reliable messaging solution for asynchronous communication between application components, whether they are running in the cloud, on the desktop, on an on-premises server, or on a mobile device.",
      "pos": [
        11416,
        11635
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Queue storage also supports managing asynchronous tasks and building process workflows.",
      "pos": [
        11636,
        11723
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A storage account can contain any number of queues.",
      "pos": [
        11726,
        11777
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A queue can contain any number of messages, up to the capacity limit of the storage account.",
      "pos": [
        11778,
        11870
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Individual messages may be up to 64 KB in size.",
      "pos": [
        11871,
        11918
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "File Storage (Preview)",
      "pos": [
        11923,
        11945
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure File storage offers cloud-based SMB 2.1 file shares, so that you can migrate legacy applications that rely on file shares to Azure quickly and without costly rewrites.",
      "pos": [
        11947,
        12120
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "With Azure File storage, applications running in Azure virtual machines or cloud services can mount a file share in the cloud, just as a desktop application mounts a typical SMB share.",
      "pos": [
        12121,
        12305
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Any number of application components can then mount and access the File storage share simultaneously.",
      "pos": [
        12306,
        12407
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since a File storage share is a standard SMB 2.1 file share, applications running in Azure can access data in the share via file sytem I/O APIs.",
      "pos": [
        12409,
        12553
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Developers can therefore leverage their existing code and skills to migrate existing applications.",
      "pos": [
        12554,
        12652
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "IT Pros can use PowerShell cmdlets to create, mount, and manage File storage shares as part of the administration of Azure applications.",
      "pos": [
        12653,
        12789
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Like the other Azure storage services, File storage exposes a REST API for accessing data in a share.",
      "pos": [
        12791,
        12892
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On-premise applications can call the File storage REST API to access data in a file share.",
      "pos": [
        12893,
        12983
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This way, an enterprise can choose to migrate some legacy applications to Azure and continue running others from within their own organization.",
      "pos": [
        12984,
        13127
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that mounting a file share is only possible for applications running in Azure; an on-premise application may only access the file share via the REST API.",
      "pos": [
        13128,
        13286
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Distributed applications can also use File storage to store and share useful application data and development and testing tools.",
      "pos": [
        13288,
        13416
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, an application may store configuration files and diagnostic data such as logs, metrics, and crash dumps in a File storage share so that they are available to multiple virtual machines or roles.",
      "pos": [
        13417,
        13623
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Developers and administrators can store utilities that they need to build or manage an application in a File storage share that is available to all components, rather than installing them on every virtual machine or role instance.",
      "pos": [
        13624,
        13854
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Access to Blob, Table, Queue, and File Resources",
      "pos": [
        13859,
        13907
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, only the storage account owner can access resources in the storage account.",
      "pos": [
        13909,
        13996
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For the security of your data, every request made against resources in your account must be authenticated.",
      "pos": [
        13997,
        14103
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Authentication relies on a Shared Key model.",
      "pos": [
        14104,
        14148
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Blobs can also be configured to support anonymous authentication.",
      "pos": [
        14149,
        14214
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your storage account is assigned two private access keys on creation that are used for authentication.",
      "pos": [
        14217,
        14319
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Having two keys ensures that your application remains available when you regularly regenerate the keys as a common security key management practice.",
      "pos": [
        14320,
        14468
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you do need to allow users controlled access to your storage resources, then you can create a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>shared access signature<ept id=\"p1\">](storage-dotnet-shared-access-signature-part-1.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        14470,
        14643
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A shared access signature is a token that can be appended to a URL that enables delegated access to a container, blob, table, or queue.",
      "pos": [
        14644,
        14779
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Anyone who possesses the token can access the resource it points to with the permissions it specifies, for the period of time that it is valid.",
      "pos": [
        14780,
        14923
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that Azure File storage does not currently support shared access signatures.",
      "pos": [
